She flipped to an empty page and noted the date. Below that, she wrote "11.5.648–13.12.648."
"Filling up old memories?" Ivory asked, looking at the old notebook. Kari nodded. "Do you think they'll let you out for Christmas? There are only a few days left."
Kari tapped twice on the lantern. "No," as Ivory had guessed. The Ice King never let Kari out, for he considered her a "flaw." She was born deaf and was the only daughter in the family, her siblings were all boys.
The same was true for Ivory. When Ivory came out as non-binary, it seemed as though the world was changing. As a punishment for this difference, Ivory was given tasks that mostly required being alone.
In addition, Ivory was also forced to serve the princess. However, it didn't bother Ivory much, since Ivory had also gained a friend.
"Your birthday is coming up soon, isn't it?" Ivory asked, thinking about the fact that the princess was turning a few days from then. Kari nodded with a sad flicker in her bright blue eyes.
"Would you like to celebrate your birthday?" Ivory asked, thinking back to the last time the princess had answered this question.
"No," Kari tapped. Ivory knew this was a difficult subject for her. Her birthday was the day she was locked in this room and her mother banished. Ivory had been a baby at the time, but she remembered how upset the servants and the city's residents had been. Ivory had heard that Eirwen was a beloved queen. And that strangely, she could foresee things that later actually came to pass.
"Now, what do you want to do?" asked Ivory. Kari looked at Ivory excitedly. She was holding a piece of paper in her hand. On it was written:
15 x 15 cm canvas
Weiß, various shades of blue
Brushes in six different sizes
Easel
"Are you asking me to get these things for you?" Ivory turned to the quiet princess, whose braids swayed back and forth from her vigorous knocking. "Yes?" Ivory giggled softly. The usually reserved princess showed so much excitement. It was the first time she had asked about something that had nothing to do with books and came from outside her room.
"Okay! Let's see each other later?" Ivory asked, stood up, and wove through the chaos of paper and notebooks.
Kari nodded, turned back to her notes, and wrapped herself in her blanket.
Ivory left the room, relieved that the princess had finally stepped out of her comfort zone and asked for things beyond her reach, like Malfarben.
Ivory ran through the corridors again and tried to ignore the gossip of the maids.
"I've heard that she is supposed to be possessed by Queen Eirwen and therefore goes into this room again and again."
"I heard that she eats children in this room."
"Doesn't she look like a man? That's not normal, is it?"
Ivory covered her ears because she couldn't ignore the gossip any longer, and she walked on. The room of the royal painter was located in the east wing, behind the second door on the left side.
Ivory approached the door, which was just as intricately decorated as Karis door. On it was depicted the White Dragon, one of the six Primordial Dragons who, according to legend, were supposed to have created Frostfell. For a history-loving painter, the White Dragon on the door made perfect sense.
Ivory opened the door and expected the usual chaos. Paint splatters everywhere, brushes and paper scattered throughout the room, easels covering every inch of the walls. Unexpectedly, a different sight presented itself. The entire room was clean, and before a red velvet background stood a chair. On the chair sat Crown Prince Aquilo, who was being painted.
"Good morning, Ivory! Would you like to watch how your future king is portrayed?" asked Aquilo and winked at Ivory.
"Excuse me, little prince," said Ivory, largely ignoring him and gathering the things the silent princess wished for. "I'm only here to pick up some supplies."
"My little girl wants to go already?" asked Aquilo. "But I want you to stay!"
"I don't, though." Ivory found the items on the list and put them in a box. "Besides, I'm not a girl."
However, the prince had a different opinion. "Oh, my dear, that's just a phase! As you get older, you'll grow out of it!" he said indistinctly.
"I have to go," said Ivory, feeling uneasy at the prince's reply. All the ugly remarks that he and others had made about Ivory's gender identity in the past came flooding back to him. I just want to get out of here.
"Are you leaving already?" Suddenly the prince appeared at the door and ignored the loud protests of the royal painter.
"That's not behavior for a future king!" said Ivory.
"Nobody will find out. The people won't believe you, and the painter will remain silent if his life is worth anything." He briefly looked at the painter and then leaned closer to Ivory. "What do you think about a date?" Ivory had been harassed before, but never by a prince, let alone the crown prince.
"Do you even know what the word 'No' means?" spat Ivory and pushed the crown prince away.
"No," answered Aquilo with a smile. Of course, the crown prince, who can have anything he desires, doesn't know what the word "no" means.
Ivory rolled her eyes. "Why do you want to go out with someone like me? You must have around 100 admirers?"
"Actually, it's 50," interrupted him Ivory, still smiling. He pushed back his hair, which whirled around in the cold air.
"Now get it! Why me? I'm a danger to the palace." Ivory crossed her arms.
"You are the most beautiful girl I've ever seen," Aquilo lifted Ivory's chin with his finger and forced her to look at him.
